description.narrative:
The proposed impact statement for GRAISEA 2 is # #improved livelihoods for women and men small-scale producers in the Southeast Asia region through more inclusive and sustainable value chains, where women demonstrate economic leadership#. This programme is the second phase of the GRAISEA programme (GRAISEA 1: A-04254) and aligns with GRAISEA#s existing theory of change and its programme structure.
The theory of change that is currently in development, aims to achieve the above mentioned impact througha combination of : #development of models and good practise at country level, for instance working with the private sector or working with finance institutions or community organisations #the dissemination of good practise from these models at country and regional levels through multi stakeholder groups and influencing of other actors (e.g. finance providers) #the creation of a regulatory environment, nationally and regionally that stimulates these changes and ensures standards
The proposed programme design spreads these elements across fourResult Areas, broadly similar to GRAISEA 1 Result Areas. #Result 1: ASEAN and its member states, and ASEAN Business Advisory Council ABAC recognize and adopt #gender transformative principles in inclusive and responsible agribusiness# (or GTP-IRA) #Result 2: Women and men small-scale producers are engaged in value chains which provide opportunities for gender transformative livelihoods and increased economic leadership and resilience (in economic and livelihood). #Result 3: Sector-wide systems, models and practices which exert a positive systemic change that empower smallholder farmers/producers and promotes Women Economic Empowerment (WEE) through Gender Transformative Principles and Inclusive Business Practices(GTP-IRA) #Result 4: An Eco System of Business Support and finance isdeveloped that enables MSMEs and Social Enterprises (SE) in the Agriculture Sector to become Sustainable, to grow and to Empower Women.
The Thematic Unit Land, Water and Pro Poor Value Chains in the Hague will be responsible for the contract management of GRAISEA 2.

participating-org.narrative: Oxfam Novib was founded in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994. Oxfam Novib is member of the Oxfam International confederation. Working together in the confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education for all, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies. Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy. Oxfam Novib’s the Hague office contributes towards this project’s implementation.
